For example, here I use echo equals false. That basically means I want to hide the code in the output. I only want to show the output for this code chunk. So here you only see the output. For example, here is a chunk of text output and here is the graphics output.

00:25:22.439 --> 00:25:41.439
So by using echo equals false you can hide the results. And there are some other options that you might be interested in. For example, I want to do the computing but for this code chunk I don't want to show you the results.

00:25:41.439 --> 00:25:59.439
So you can use the chunk option results equals hide and that basically means I want to run this code chunk but I don't want to show the text output. So you see when you print the p-values the printed output is actually hidden here.

00:25:59.439 --> 00:26:24.439
So there are many, many other options that you can use. If you are in RStudio you can just hit the tab key to do some auto-completion. So there are a whole bunch of chunk options that you might want to use. And you will find the documentation for all these chunk options on the NITR website later.

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:45.439
And that's how we can play with the text output. And actually you can also, for example, change the parameters for graphics output. For example, here the size of this plot is 5x7 inches.

00:26:45.439 --> 00:27:05.439
So if I want to make this plot taller so I can specify the chunk option figure.height equals 10 which means the height will be 10 inches. If I change the size all I need to do is just click this button again and the output will be updated.

00:27:05.439 --> 00:27:27.439
So there are some other chunk options associated with the graphics output. For example, the device option so you can use a bunch of graphics devices like PNG device or SVG device and many others.

00:27:27.439 --> 00:27:45.439
So this is how you can play with the graphics output. And sometimes your code chunk might be time consuming so let me just show you a quick example of how you can deal with that situation.

00:27:45.439 --> 00:28:07.439
So if your code chunk is time consuming you can actually use the chunk option cache equals true. So when you turn on this chunk option the results will be cached. So you see when I click this button RStudio will pause for 5 seconds here and then show me the output.

00:28:07.439 --> 00:28:27.439
And now the second time when I click this button if I don't change the code here then it will just load the old results from the cache database directly into the R session and show you the output. So now you can see the output immediately instead of waiting for 5 seconds here.

00:28:27.439 --> 00:28:48.439
So that's the feature for cache and let's see what else. And also if you don't want to use the R language in your code chunks you can also use some other languages using the chunk option engine.

00:28:48.439 --> 00:29:15.439
So for example here is a Python code chunk so I just need to specify the chunk option engine equals Python and then I will be able to run this code chunk using Python instead of R. So when I click this button R will launch Python to split this character string into a vector here of three elements.

00:29:15.439 --> 00:29:40.439
There are some other chunk options that can also work with the option engine equals Python and there are some other languages supported in Knitter for example you can use Rcpp to write some C++ code so all you have to do is to specify engine equals Rcpp and now you just write some C++ code.

00:29:40.439 --> 00:29:49.439
Similarly just click this button and Knitter will compile this C++ code chunks and show you the results in the output.

00:29:49.439 --> 00:30:12.439
So these are just some very basic features of the Knitter package and you can also have some applications using the Knitter package and one application is that you can build websites using Knitter.

00:30:13.439 --> 00:30:31.439
For example this website Rcpp gallery is built using Knitter and Rcpp so you can see this is basically like a blog site so there are a couple of posts.

00:30:32.439 --> 00:30:53.439
Seems the internet connection is not good here but you can check out by yourself later and basically this is based on R Markdown and there are some C++ code chunks in the blog posts and you can compile all these blog posts using Knitter.

00:30:54.439 --> 00:31:06.439
There is also another website called rpubs.com so that basically contains a lot of HTML documents compiled from Knitter.

00:31:07.439 --> 00:31:25.439
For example here is a peer assessment project one I'm not sure if that's from the Coursera course or something else but basically you can see the code chunks and the graphics and things like that.

00:31:26.439 --> 00:31:52.439
To publish to this website you can actually click this button in RStudio called publish so if you have registered on rpubs.com you can upload your reports to that website and there are a lot of other excellent examples on this website you can check out later by yourself.

00:31:53.439 --> 00:32:16.439
Another application of Knitter is that you can write your package vignettes if you are a package author so basically here is the source code for the Knitter package and I have a directory called vignettes and then I have a couple of R Markdown documents under this directory.

00:32:17.439 --> 00:32:41.439
To write a package vignette using Knitter you just need to specify the vignette engine to be a certain engine in the Knitter package and then you specify the title for this vignette and when you compile this package and install it you will see a list of vignettes like this.

00:32:42.439 --> 00:32:45.439
So here are the built-in vignettes in the Knitter package.

00:32:46.439 --> 00:32:52.439
So I just want to show you one of them which is this one called the Dockel classic style.

00:32:53.439 --> 00:32:55.439
This is a very interesting layout in my eyes.

00:32:56.439 --> 00:33:03.439
So for this layout you can see the narratives and the code and the output are arranged side by side.

00:33:04.439 --> 00:33:23.439
So if you want to hide the code you can just press the key T on your keyboard so you can just read the narratives and graphics output and if you want to hide the narratives you don't care about narratives you just want to read the code you can hide the narratives and just read the code.

00:33:24.439 --> 00:33:28.439
And for most people probably this side by side layout is most appropriate.

00:33:29.439 --> 00:33:35.439
So this is how you can play with the Dockel style in Knitter.

00:33:36.439 --> 00:33:40.439
So there are a couple of resources to learn more about Knitter.

00:33:40.439 --> 00:33:48.439
The first one I want to recommend is just the online documentation for this package which is at ua.name.knitter.

00:33:49.439 --> 00:34:03.439
And if you are just too rich you can just buy this book I wrote last year Dynamic Documents with R and Knitter but you don't really have to buy that one because I have very comprehensive documentation for this package online.

00:34:04.439 --> 00:34:10.439
So just a last comment on reproducible research which is the topic for today.

00:34:11.439 --> 00:34:16.439
So reproducible research is really not a trivial thing.

00:34:17.439 --> 00:34:20.439
I mean there are a lot of things to consider when you write a report.

00:34:21.439 --> 00:34:26.439
Just by using Knitter does not guarantee that your report is reproducible.

00:34:27.439 --> 00:34:37.439
For example you might be using some absolute paths in your reports which will not be reproducible on other people's computers.

00:34:38.439 --> 00:34:41.439
There are just a lot of things to consider.

00:34:42.439 --> 00:34:49.439
But I guess Knitter will be helpful at least as the first step to reproducible research.

00:34:50.439 --> 00:35:01.439
So I just hope all of you can be patient enough to wait for this area of reproducible research to grow just like this tree.

00:35:02.439 --> 00:35:08.439
And finally hopefully we will be living in a wonderful world of reproducible research.

00:35:09.439 --> 00:35:10.439
Thank you.

00:35:11.439 --> 00:35:14.439
I will hand over to Kevin.

00:35:15.439 --> 00:35:16.439
Thanks Yihui.

00:35:17.439 --> 00:35:22.439
So now I'm going to talk about PackRat which is a dependency management system for R.

00:35:23.439 --> 00:35:29.439
So given everything that Jeff and Yihui have taught us about trying to write reproducible research.

00:35:30.439 --> 00:35:38.439
One thing that we want to be able to do is take the R environment that we use to produce these reports and try and preserve that over time.

00:35:39.439 --> 00:35:48.439
So PackRat is an R package that helps us manage these R projects, R package dependencies in a way that is reproducible.

00:35:49.439 --> 00:35:54.439
So when you form an analysis you're going to use different R packages.

00:35:55.439 --> 00:35:59.439
Say you got them from CRAN or if you live on the bleeding edge maybe you got them from GitHub.

00:36:00.439 --> 00:36:06.439
But when you do an analysis or write an R project you want to make sure that you can save these packages over time.

00:36:06.439 --> 00:36:12.439
Say you publish this as research and one or two years down the line you need to run that again.

00:36:13.439 --> 00:36:21.439
You want to make sure you can reproduce that exact same results with the exact same environment that you used originally when forming the analysis.

00:36:22.439 --> 00:36:26.439
Another thing about this is you want your projects to be isolated.

00:36:27.439 --> 00:36:33.439
So in the current state of the R world when you install a package it goes into your global library.

00:36:33.439 --> 00:36:40.439
So every project that you write on your computer has access to that package and that's often useful.

00:36:41.439 --> 00:36:53.439
In some occasions you want to be able to have a private library for each project in case one project depends on one version of a package and another project depends on another version of a package.

00:36:54.439 --> 00:37:00.439
So PackRat gives you a means of isolating these package dependencies within a library for each project.

00:37:00.439 --> 00:37:14.439
And last of all we want this to be portable so that if you need to collaborate with people on alternative machines they can build the same R environment using the same system from your PackRat project.

00:37:15.439 --> 00:37:19.439
So PackRat makes it easy to install those packages for a particular R project.

00:37:20.439 --> 00:37:32.439
Part of the reason why the PackRat development was motivated is for those of you who have either been in research for a while or done some work and come back to it a year later.

00:37:33.439 --> 00:37:38.439
You've probably come back to your code and asked first of all who wrote this garbage code?

00:37:39.439 --> 00:37:47.439
Unfortunately one of the side effects of becoming a better programmer is realizing that the code you wrote before is probably not as good.

00:37:47.439 --> 00:38:00.439
And unfortunately if you come back to code a year later unless you wrote it in a reproducible nicely commented way you're going to struggle to recollect exactly what you did and how you did it.

00:38:03.439 --> 00:38:07.439
Another thing is you might have used say Lattice which is an R package for generating plots.

00:38:08.439 --> 00:38:10.439
You used that to make some figures before.

00:38:10.439 --> 00:38:19.439
But now when you try to run it with your new version of R, say you updated it recently, all of a sudden your plotting code is just throwing errors at you.

00:38:20.439 --> 00:38:26.439
For some reason a Lattice update has broken your code and you know your code didn't change but Lattice did.

00:38:27.439 --> 00:38:32.439
So now you have to figure out what changed and how you can fix your code or find the old version of Lattice.

00:38:32.439 --> 00:38:37.439
Say you used the NLME package for fitting non-linear mixed effects models.

00:38:38.439 --> 00:38:40.439
And when you ran it before everything went fine.

00:38:41.439 --> 00:38:44.439
You showed the results to your boss or you published it as research.

00:38:45.439 --> 00:38:48.439
The model convergence criteria everything worked okay.

00:38:49.439 --> 00:38:56.439
You come back and try to re-run it a year later and something has changed underneath NLME and suddenly it's complaining about model convergence.

00:38:57.439 --> 00:39:04.439
I guess something changed in there and how they are fitting the parameters and this makes you feel pretty uncomfortable.

00:39:05.439 --> 00:39:14.439
Suddenly the environment you used to produce the results before, you can't reproduce that with this new environment with the updated version of NLME.

00:39:15.439 --> 00:39:22.439
Another one is not every R package you use is going to be on CRAN or GitHub or an external repository.

00:39:22.439 --> 00:39:29.439
Say you got it from collaborators who put it and they just share it through email or you got on a USB stick from someone.

00:39:30.439 --> 00:39:32.439
You really don't want to have to go and hunt that back down.

00:39:33.439 --> 00:39:38.439
It'd be really nice if we were able to just keep that package in a project and save it over time.

00:39:39.439 --> 00:39:45.439
So PackRat helps us solve this problem by one, we make sure that package sources are stored alongside your project.

00:39:46.439 --> 00:39:58.439
And we track the package version so that if you update R but you need to return to an old version of a R project, you can roll back and reinstall that package for some reason.

00:39:59.439 --> 00:40:07.439
So the way I like to think about it is PackRat lets you build the sandbox in which an analysis can run and it helps you ensure that this sandbox will persist over time.

00:40:08.439 --> 00:40:20.439
And as I said before, one of the benefits but also problems with the current system for R packages is that everything gets installed into a global library.

00:40:21.439 --> 00:40:24.439
So all projects on your system have access to the same library.

00:40:25.439 --> 00:40:30.439
But for a particular version of R, only one version of a particular package can be installed at a time.

00:40:30.439 --> 00:40:37.439
This is problematic if you have multiple projects on your system and one depends on a current version of a package, say R3P.

00:40:38.439 --> 00:40:43.439
And another one depends on a newer version of R3P which maybe doesn't work with your older one.

00:40:44.439 --> 00:40:46.439
But you want to leverage the features of that for new projects.

00:40:48.439 --> 00:40:55.439
So we want to be able to isolate these package dependencies for each project and PackRat helps us do that.

00:40:55.439 --> 00:40:59.439
So PackRat does this by giving each project its own private PackRat library.

00:41:00.439 --> 00:41:07.439
So if you don't know what a library is in R parlance, a library is just a folder of installed R packages.

00:41:08.439 --> 00:41:15.439
So when you make a call to the library function which is kind of poorly named because it loads a package from a library.

00:41:16.439 --> 00:41:21.439
Say we use library dplyr to load the dplyr package from dplyr.

00:41:21.439 --> 00:41:26.439
Say we use library dplyr to load the dplyr package from the library.

00:41:27.439 --> 00:41:30.439
R will attempt to load dplyr by default from that global library.

00:41:32.439 --> 00:41:40.439
If you use PackRat to manage an R project on the other hand, PackRat will ensure that R loads that package from a private library instead.

00:41:41.439 --> 00:41:49.439
The other nice thing is because we do it this way with PackRat, it doesn't interfere with any normal workflows.

00:41:50.439 --> 00:41:56.439
Any calls to install.packages, devtools install github, bioclite if you're a bioconductor person.

00:41:57.439 --> 00:41:59.439
These will also get installed into the private library.

00:42:00.439 --> 00:42:07.439
So you can ensure that installing new packages for one project does not break any analysis you have for another project.

00:42:08.439 --> 00:42:17.439
And because PackRat collects all of these project dependencies and it ensures that it is portable across different systems.

00:42:18.439 --> 00:42:26.439
So if you're working with collaborators, you can ensure everyone working on a Pitch-to-Curve project is using the same version of any R packages your project depends on.

00:42:27.439 --> 00:42:33.439
So you don't have to worry about, oh you're getting a bug, is it because you have the newest version and I'm using this different version of this package.

00:42:34.439 --> 00:42:39.439
When people collaborate on a PackRat project, you ensure everyone works in the same environment.

00:42:40.439 --> 00:42:45.439
All these things are better done with a demo, so I'll switch to RStudio.

00:42:46.439 --> 00:42:49.439
Oops, we can get rid of that.

00:42:50.439 --> 00:42:53.439
So let's start a new project in RStudio.

00:42:54.439 --> 00:43:00.439
So with the latest RStudio daily builds, we have really nice PackRat integration.

00:43:00.439 --> 00:43:03.439
So the first thing you'll see is, let me go back.

00:43:04.439 --> 00:43:12.439
If I go to start a new project from a new directory, an empty project, we now have this new tab, Use PackRat with this project.

00:43:13.439 --> 00:43:20.439
So let's say I'll make a new project called Omelettes because I want to analyze different ways of making omelettes.

00:43:21.439 --> 00:43:29.439
So I do this, PackRat does some work to set up the project here, and RStudio bumps us and we have a new project.

00:43:30.439 --> 00:43:35.439
So we're in the Omelettes project and everything looks the same as before.

00:43:36.439 --> 00:43:47.439
The only thing that is slightly different now is if we go over to the packages pane, we'll see that we now have two libraries, two places where our packages live.

00:43:47.439 --> 00:43:50.439
We have the PackRat library and we have the system library.

00:43:51.439 --> 00:43:58.439
So what we have done is we've isolated any dependencies and everything we install is now going to live in this PackRat library.

00:43:59.439 --> 00:44:08.439
Let's say I want to use StringR for some bit of code that I'm running here.

00:44:09.439 --> 00:44:18.439
So first of all, I don't have StringR. It might have been in my user library, but because I'm using PackRat, that library is hidden from us.

00:44:19.439 --> 00:44:21.439
So we're going to go and make sure that we install it.

00:44:22.439 --> 00:44:25.439
And notice that it gets put right into our PackRat library.

00:44:25.439 --> 00:44:29.439
So we have StringR from CRAN version 0.6.2.

00:44:30.439 --> 00:44:35.439
And you might have seen that PackRat immediately took that and said, oh, I see you installed a package StringR.

00:44:36.439 --> 00:44:38.439
I'm going to track that. I'm going to track its source.

00:44:39.439 --> 00:44:45.439
And so you have this package in your library and you have StringR in your PackRat private library.

00:44:46.439 --> 00:44:47.439
So now we can use StringR.

00:44:48.439 --> 00:44:58.439
We can call strc of, let's see, if I want to concatenate strings, great, I can use StringR there.

00:44:59.439 --> 00:45:09.439
Similarly, let's say I want to install, let's say, dplyr.

00:45:10.439 --> 00:45:13.439
So dplyr has a large number of dependencies.

00:45:13.439 --> 00:45:15.439
So it'll take a little bit of time to get that.

00:45:16.439 --> 00:45:20.439
But fortunately, we're just downloading, so it will take a little bit of time to install.

00:45:26.439 --> 00:45:30.439
So let's say we don't want to wait for that.

00:45:36.439 --> 00:45:37.439
I guess I can't pause there.

00:45:40.439 --> 00:45:41.439
I'll let it keep going.

00:45:44.439 --> 00:45:49.439
So you see, as the packages are installed, you're getting PackRat to track them.

00:45:55.439 --> 00:45:57.439
So now these packages are tracked in our PackRat library.

00:45:58.439 --> 00:46:00.439
And sorry, I'll go and get dplyr once more.

00:46:01.439 --> 00:46:05.439
The initial bump of getting the packages in your PackRat library is a little bit slow,

00:46:06.439 --> 00:46:10.439
but it's worth having your project reproducible over time.

00:46:13.439 --> 00:46:15.439
I'll just write some code making use of dplyr.

00:46:18.439 --> 00:46:20.439
Apologies for the wait while it compiles dplyr.

00:46:23.439 --> 00:46:27.439
Kevin, we're getting a few questions about the size of the PackRat repositories.

00:46:28.439 --> 00:46:30.439
Can you comment on how big you'd expect these to get?

00:46:31.439 --> 00:46:35.439
So with PackRat repositories, yes, they will grow in size

00:46:36.439 --> 00:46:38.439
because you keep all of your package sources

00:46:38.439 --> 00:46:44.439
and you keep a library of packages for each PackRat project.

00:46:45.439 --> 00:46:48.439
So they do get a little bit bigger, but by default,

00:46:49.439 --> 00:46:52.439
if you want to rebuild or share a PackRat project,

00:46:53.439 --> 00:46:55.439
all you need is the PackRat lock file.

00:46:59.439 --> 00:47:01.439
You'll see there's this PackRat.lock file,

00:47:02.439 --> 00:47:07.439
which tells you what version of a package you have and what its source was.

00:47:08.439 --> 00:47:13.439
If you trade that around, that's all people need to share and restore a package.

00:47:16.439 --> 00:47:19.439
So now, suppose I call PackRat status.

00:47:20.439 --> 00:47:22.439
It tells me that everything is up to date.

00:47:23.439 --> 00:47:27.439
Now suppose I remove a package that my project depends on.

00:47:28.439 --> 00:47:29.439
Say I remove dplyr now.

00:47:30.439 --> 00:47:32.439
So notice how in this file here, I'm calling dplyr.

00:47:33.439 --> 00:47:36.439
So I have my project needs dplyr to run.

00:47:36.439 --> 00:47:40.439
And RStudio will go and say, hey, you're using dplyr on your project.

00:47:41.439 --> 00:47:43.439
I saw it was removed, but you're using it.

00:47:44.439 --> 00:47:46.439
So I think you probably want it in your library.

00:47:47.439 --> 00:47:49.439
So it instructs you to update the library.

00:47:50.439 --> 00:47:52.439
It tells you that these packages have changed in PackRat

00:47:53.439 --> 00:47:55.439
and you can use restore to apply these changes,

00:47:56.439 --> 00:48:01.439
which restores the library based on the state of your PackRat lock file or the last snapshot.

00:48:02.439 --> 00:48:03.439
So we do that.

00:48:04.439 --> 00:48:06.439
We see that a call is made to PackRat restore.

00:48:07.439 --> 00:48:12.439
So restore takes the last consistent state of your project and applies it to the library.

00:48:13.439 --> 00:48:15.439
So it's reinstalling dplyr from CRAN and unfortunately,

00:48:16.439 --> 00:48:17.439
I'm compiling from source, so it's a bit slow.

00:48:18.439 --> 00:48:21.439
Normally, if you're running a CRAN build of R, this won't be a problem.

00:48:22.439 --> 00:48:25.439
But the point is here that PackRat tracked dplyr.

00:48:26.439 --> 00:48:27.439
It knew what version it was.

00:48:28.439 --> 00:48:29.439
It knew where to get it.

00:48:29.439 --> 00:48:32.439
And so it can go out, grab the package and install it

00:48:33.439 --> 00:48:40.439
or install it from local sources as all the PackRat package sources get cached as well.

00:48:45.439 --> 00:48:48.439
So we also see that, you know, if we didn't have access to the Internet in dplyr,

00:48:49.439 --> 00:48:54.439
we have the exact package sources for dplyr version 0.2 to use as well.

00:48:55.439 --> 00:49:00.439
One of the things that we saw earlier was we have this idea of what is known by PackRat,

00:49:01.439 --> 00:49:03.439
which is shown in this column here.

00:49:04.439 --> 00:49:06.439
And what is currently in your library, which is right here.

00:49:07.439 --> 00:49:15.439
And normally, you have the action PackRat snapshot for taking the state of your library

00:49:16.439 --> 00:49:18.439
and applying it into the PackRat lock files.

00:49:19.439 --> 00:49:21.439
You say, I want to preserve the current state of my library over time.

00:49:22.439 --> 00:49:28.439
And PackRat restore for taking the state of the last consistent library state

00:49:29.439 --> 00:49:30.439
and applying it to your library.

00:49:31.439 --> 00:49:34.439
But right now, because we're a consistent state, both of those actions do nothing.

00:49:35.439 --> 00:49:41.439
One thing, the two things you need to know about to use PackRat is the snapshot,

00:49:42.439 --> 00:49:46.439
the current state, the current consistent state of your projects are dependencies

00:49:47.439 --> 00:49:50.439
and the private library of packages that power your project.

00:49:51.439 --> 00:49:55.439
So we have two main verbs for interacting with these two components.

00:49:56.439 --> 00:49:59.439
PackRat snapshot records the package versions used by a project

00:50:00.439 --> 00:50:03.439
and downloads their source code for storage with the project.

00:50:04.439 --> 00:50:08.439
And PackRat restore applies the previous snapshot to a project,

00:50:09.439 --> 00:50:11.439
building packages from source as necessary.

00:50:12.439 --> 00:50:15.439
So once you have your project in a consistent state,

00:50:16.439 --> 00:50:19.439
you want to save the current state of the world, use PackRat status to do that.

00:50:19.439 --> 00:50:24.439
If you want to restore that previous state, say you've removed packages

00:50:25.439 --> 00:50:30.439
or you received something from a collaborator, use restore to restore the library.

00:50:31.439 --> 00:50:33.439
So I went through that demo.

00:50:34.439 --> 00:50:37.439
So we saw these init to initialize a PackRat project.

00:50:38.439 --> 00:50:40.439
PackRat saves the current state of your library to the lock file.

00:50:41.439 --> 00:50:43.439
Restore restores the lock file to the library.

00:50:44.439 --> 00:50:47.439
We saw this on the RStudio new package call.

00:50:48.439 --> 00:50:50.439
We call snapshot.

00:50:51.439 --> 00:50:54.439
It takes the current state of the library and saves it to the lock file.

00:50:55.439 --> 00:50:56.439
We call restore.

00:50:57.439 --> 00:51:00.439
If we've lost those packages, it restores them based on the state of the lock file.

00:51:01.439 --> 00:51:07.439
Now, I didn't show it in the demo, but we can, of course, use packages from GitHub.

00:51:08.439 --> 00:51:11.439
So we have a PackRat function or DevTools function for installing packages from GitHub.

00:51:12.439 --> 00:51:16.439
Say we want to use the development version of RCPP.

00:51:17.439 --> 00:51:20.439
We can do that and we would get the development version,

00:51:21.439 --> 00:51:24.439
which if we had a previous version from CRAN, we'd see that PackRat is upgrading it

00:51:25.439 --> 00:51:29.439
from the CRAN 0.11.2 to the development 0.11.2.1.

00:51:30.439 --> 00:51:35.439
The last thing we can do that makes it easy to share projects is we have bundle and unbundle.

00:51:36.439 --> 00:51:44.439
So bundle packages up every file within a project along with the parts of the PackRat ecosystem

00:51:44.439 --> 00:51:46.439
that are necessary to rebuild the project.

00:51:47.439 --> 00:51:54.439
And you have control over whether you want to include the package sources

00:51:55.439 --> 00:51:58.439
or the package library, which you usually don't want to do.

00:51:59.439 --> 00:52:01.439
You want to rebuild that on other systems if necessary.

00:52:02.439 --> 00:52:05.439
But you can include the sources if you want to have them locally for rebuild.

00:52:05.439 --> 00:52:14.439
The other thing is we expect PackRat to work nicely with version control.

00:52:15.439 --> 00:52:19.439
So the PackRat lock file keeps the last consistent library state.

00:52:20.439 --> 00:52:25.439
But if you're tracking a project with GitHub, you can track that lock file over time.

00:52:26.439 --> 00:52:31.439
And so you can roll back to any state from a lock file within that project if you need to.

00:52:32.439 --> 00:52:36.439
The main goals or objectives of PackRat is to create a nice little environment

00:52:37.439 --> 00:52:41.439
for your R projects to run and live in and keep that reproducible over time.

00:52:42.439 --> 00:52:47.439
And we want to make it as easy as possible to use both from PackRat and from RStudio

00:52:48.439 --> 00:52:51.439
to manage your R dependencies over time.

00:52:52.439 --> 00:52:55.439
And of course, right now we only manage R package dependencies,

00:52:55.439 --> 00:53:01.439
but there are also other software for managing entire operating systems or environments.

00:53:02.439 --> 00:53:04.439
For example, Docker, if you're interested in that.

00:53:05.439 --> 00:53:09.439
And so currently PackRat is not yet on CRAN.

00:53:10.439 --> 00:53:12.439
It is only available on GitHub.

00:53:13.439 --> 00:53:19.439
So if you want to install the latest version of PackRat, you can close this project.

00:53:20.439 --> 00:53:23.439
So we leave PackRat temporarily.

00:53:23.439 --> 00:53:30.439
And if you have the DevTools package, you can install it with a call to DevTools install GitHub.

00:53:31.439 --> 00:53:32.439
And so that'll go out and grab it and install it.

00:53:33.439 --> 00:53:36.439
So now you have it available for use with any projects on your machine.

